<html><title>Chile Should Join NAFTA -- Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg"><center>
<h3><i>CHILE SHOULD JOIN NAFTA</i></h3>

By Ricardo Matte Equiguren<br>
Director of Economic Programs<br>
Instituto Libertad y Desarrollo<br>
Santiago, Chile<br>
Committee Brief No. 19<br>
October 19, 1995<br>
<hr width=50%></center>
<P>
Note: Ricardo Matte Equiguren was a Visiting Fellow at <a href="/heritage/">The Heritage Foundation</a> during the summer of 1995<p>
<b>INTRODUCTION</b>
<P>
The prompt accession of Chile to the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) would be a powerful incentive for other Latin American countries to accelerate the pace of economic liberalization and democratic reforms. These reforms constitute a necessary institutional framework upon which a successful Free Trade Area of the Americas can be built. Conversely, delaying Chile's entry into NAFTA could paralyze the consolidation of capitalist democracy not only in Chile, but also throughout all of Latin America. Similarly, if negotiations imposed conditions on Chile that are unrelated to free trade, such as side agreements on labor and the environment, Chile's economy would be damaged. Chile, therefore, would likely balk at including such agreements in a NAFTA expansion agreement.
<p>
Free trade agreements like NAFTA are the most efficient way to open up intra-regional markets. They eliminate most tariffs on trade, substantially reduce non-tariff trade barriers, and remove restrictions on the free flow of capital. Since average tariff levels are clearly higher in Chile than in the United States, the tariff elimination schedule resulting from Chile's accession to NAFTA would encourage a rapid expansion of American exports to Chile and more high-wage jobs for American workers.
<p>
Chile's quick accession to NAFTA would be a reaffirmation of U.S. leadership in the construction of a Free Trade Area of the Americas. Other Latin American countries are following the situation very carefully. They are waiting for the U.S. Congress to approve a new "fast track" negotiating authority and are wondering whether the Clinton Administration can wrap up a NAFTA deal with Chile that will pass muster in Congress. At stake is a pledge by President Clinton at the Summit of the Americas in Miami that Chile would become NAFTA's fourth member before mid-1996. If that timetable is not met, the pace of economic and democratic reform could slacken in many Latin American countries where there still is much popular and political resistance to open markets and true democracy.
<p>
NAFTA would encourage faster growth of American exports to Chile, but Chile also would benefit from the removal of some non-tariff barriers that affect Chilean exports to the U.S. market. A NAFTA agreement would shield Chilean producers from protectionist tendencies in the U.S. that fluctuate with the business cycle and are sensitive to a wide variety of special-interest groups. Similarly, the trade dispute settlement mechanism that would form part of a NAFTA deal would provide added security for Chilean exporters. 
<p>
For Chile, however, the greatest benefit of joining NAFTA is that the agreement could provide the institutional insurance Chile needs to resist domestic pressures for abandoning the free-market model. By supporting a path of more stable and higher economic growth, accession to NAFTA would be a decisive step in placing Chile in the developed world more quickly. Membership in NAFTA would encourage more foreign investment in Chile by dramatically reducing the perception of risk associated with investing in a country which, despite the high and sustained rates of development achieved in the past two decades, could still repudiate the free-market policies that have been maintained successfully since the mid-1970s.
<p>

<b>INTERNATIONAL FRAMEWORK FOR FREE-MARKET POLICY</b>
<P>

NAFTA would establish an institutional framework to compel the government of Chile to guarantee the long-term stability and continuity of sound free-market policies. It also would create permanent barriers against tax increases, exchange controls, and other interventionist actions that could trigger an immediate decline in country risk perceptions about Chile. On July 11, 1995, Standard and Poor's upgraded its rating for Chile's sovereign long-term foreign debt from BBB+ to A-, placing Chile in the same top credit rating category assigned to successful Southeast Asian economies. Joining NAFTA probably would make the needed difference in raising Chile's credit rating to the highest level normally given to the most developed countries. 
<p>
Since 1974, U.S. investors in Chile have accounted for almost 50 percent of registered foreign investment and 40 percent of realized foreign investment. Following Chile's accession to NAFTA, these percentages should grow rapidly as investment restrictions are liberalized in such key economic sectors as banking and financial services -- one of the fastest-growing economic activities today in Latin America. 
<p>
The accession of Chile to NAFTA undoubtedly would expose the country to significantly greater competition, but it also would open up a fast-growing new world of trade and investment opportunities. However, in order to take full advantage of those opportunities, Chile must rise to the greatest challenge it faces today:  Chile must become more productive, competitive, and efficient. This challenge will require better leadership from a government committed to perfecting and consolidating the free-market policies responsible for Chile's track record of sustained high economic growth since 1985. Fortunately, the timing of the challenge could not be better for Chile.
<p>
Chile has won international praise and respect for the success of its free-market model and for its successful transition from military regime to freely elected democratic government. Paradoxically, however, since democracy was restored at the beginning of the 1990s, the pace of free market reform has slowed in Chile. In recent years, the Chilean government has raised taxes, made the country's labor laws more rigid, increased public spending excessively, and expanded its regulatory powers. Moreover, the government has failed to continue opening the economy. The government also has paralyzed further privatizations of state-owned companies and has ignored the need to facilitate private-sector participation in the provision of human and physical capital infrastructure. As a result, the competitiveness of the Chilean economy has been weakened, although the private sector has made remarkable strides in becoming more efficient and productive during this period. Thanks to these efforts, Chile is well-positioned today to improve its competitiveness if the government of President Eduardo Frei rectifies its present course. Accession to NAFTA would be an important catalyst for ensuring that President Frei makes these necessary changes.
<p>

<b>THE STRONGEST ECONOMY IN LATIN AMERICA</b>
<p>
Chile is at the forefront of developing nations. For the past 11 years, the economy has grown at an average annual rate of 6.3 percent. This growth has been accompanied by a steady reduction of inflation. In recent months, the yearly inflation rate has been as low as 7.5 percent, while unemployment has reached levels of 5.5 percent. The commitment of Chile's independent Central Bank to sound monetary policies has been decisive in bringing down yearly inflation to single digits. 
<p>
The public sector has been downsized to less than a third of what it was only two decades ago through a process of aggressive privatization and rationalization. One important consequence of this process has been a dramatic increase in private and public-sector savings. The stated goal of fiscal policy has been to maintain a balanced budget, but in practice, the government in recent years actually has maintained a permanent budget surplus equivalent to about 2 percent of GDP. Chile created this budget surplus by reducing the tax burden on individuals and corporations and by drastically reducing current expenditures from the equivalent of 30 percent of GDP in 1984 to 18 percent of GDP in 1994. Taxes also declined during the 1980s, from 19 percent of GDP in 1984 to 15 percent by the end of that decade, although since then they have increased again to about 17 percent of GDP. Nevertheless, the economy's tax structure is efficient and provides a stable income flow to the treasury, as well as a positive incentive to increase private savings.
<p>
One of Chile's principal economic strengths today is its high level of domestic savings, which was about 25 percent of GDP in 1994. These savings underpin investment levels equivalent to 27 percent of GDP. High levels of savings differentiate the Chilean economy from its neighbors not only in Latin America, but in all of the Western Hemisphere, including the United States. Savings are an important factor in Chile's economic and financial stability, shielding the country from the normal volatility of short-term capital flows. 
<p>
Another important feature of Chile's economic stability is the development and depth of its capital markets. The strength and solvency of Chile's capital markets is one of the characteristics that most distinguishes the country from the rest of Latin America. In addition, Chile's consolidated banking system is not only highly capitalized and profitable; it also is the most soundly supervised system in the region. 
<p>
The growth of Chile's capital markets and savings levels is tied directly to the successful privatization of the country's social security system during the early 1980s. The traditional pay-as-you-go system managed by the government was replaced with a privately managed and competitive system of individual capitalization. The companies that manage these pension funds compete for savings deposits, and workers can decide for themselves what percentage of their income they wish to place in the pension funds. As a result, the national level of savings has climbed impressively, adding depth to Chile's capital markets and favoring a more efficient allocation of resources for investment and savings.
<p>
The key to Chile's success in achieving sustained economic growth has been the outstanding performance of the country's export industry. Twenty years ago, copper accounted for 77 percent of Chile's total exports. Today, copper accounts for 37 percent of the country's export package. Moreover, Chilean exporters have been very adept at diversifying products and creating new markets. The geographical spread of Chile's exports currently is distributed almost evenly among the European Union, Latin America, the United States, Japan, and the rest of Asia. Argentina and Brazil are Chile's most important trading partners in Latin America.
<P>
Chile has been reducing its import duties unilaterally since the mid-1970s. The average tariff is now 11 percent. This policy of unilateral tariff cuts was bolstered by Chile's strong adherence to the multilateral efforts of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). Free trade agreements negotiated with Chile's main trading partners in Latin America have played a positive role. Chile is a full member of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation group (APEC) and is becoming a free trade associate of Mercosur, the South American integration group that includes Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay, and Paraguay. 
<p>
During the last ten years, there has been a dramatic improvement in the level of Chile's external indebtedness in relation to GDP. The country's external debt has declined from nearly 120 percent of GDP in 1984 to nearly 40 percent of GDP in 1994. Over the same period, the servicing of that debt -- payments of principal plus interest -- declined from the equivalent of 35 percent of Chile's total exports a decade ago to less than 8 percent today. Chile's external debt in 1994 -- less foreign assets -- was equivalent to only 15 percent of GDP. 
<p>
Chile's social progress during the past twenty years has been as outstanding as its economic performance. For example, the infant mortality rate was reduced from 66 per thousand live births in 1973 to 15 per thousand in 1991. Access to safe water in urban areas increased from 67 percent to 98 percent of the urban population, and life expectancy at birth of the population grew from 64 years in the mid-1970s to 72 years at the beginning of the 1990s. Real per capita GDP more than doubled during the same period, measured in 1994 dollars, from $1,715 in 1973 to $3,719 in 1994.
<p>

<b>ADDING VALUE </b>
<P>
Chile is leading the current wave of structural economic reforms in Latin America, but there still is much room for improvement. To maintain high rates of economic growth, Chile must achieve significant increases in investment and savings -- both public and private -- and economic policy must be managed with great care. In this respect, a crucial factor will be a renewed government commitment to two broad policies that were developed during the early stages of the reform process in Chile. 
<p>
The first policy focused on providing incentives to private enterprise by reducing the size of government and thereby expanding the spaces available to private initiative. The creation of free-market conditions to assure the private sector's health and development was an integral part of this policy. The second broad policy was that the government should not interfere with the economy or try to steer the market's behavior, even under the pretext of acting for the "common good," as it has been doing recently. The Chilean government must understand that its proper role is to ensure that markets operate efficiently. Thus, governmental regulation should not distort markets, but facilitate their creation. 
<P>
A number of important structural reforms are still pending in Chile today. For instance, the still-high uniform tariff level of 11 percent must be reduced unilaterally in order to expand Chile's international trade, and regulations governing balance of payments capital transactions must be liberalized. In addition, investment in human capital must be improved and rationalized by reforming education and health care. A system of private concessions must be implemented to build the physical infrastructure that Chile must have in order to become more competitive internationally. Private investors must be allowed to finance, build, and operate ports, airports, and water and sewage systems. Fortunately, the legislation for most of these reforms is already in place or under discussion in the Chilean Congress.
<p>
The accession of Chile to NAFTA will stimulate a permanent inflow of international resources, causing the peso to appreciate in value. This means that, in order to prevent any loss of international competitiveness, Chile must increase its domestic savings levels from around 25 percent of GDP to at least 30 percent of GDP, and it must do so quickly. This can be achieved by cutting back public expenditures and improving the economy's tax structure by reducing the tax on personal and corporate savings. Before joining NAFTA, the Frei government also must address structural weaknesses by further liberalizing trade, moving toward capital account convertibility, and opening up the financial sector.
<p>
There is no reason to delay these structural reforms. For many years, Chile has enjoyed the economic benefits created by the unilateral reduction of its import duties. There is no need to wait for a NAFTA deal before carrying out these reforms. In fact, Chile's hand in the NAFTA negotiations will be strengthened if the Frei government acts quickly. Moreover, the NAFTA negotiations should not pre-empt or slow the process of opening up unilaterally to other countries and regions, thus minimizing the potential effects of any trade diversion that NAFTA might cause.
<p>

<b>REAFFIRMING U.S. LEADERSHIP</b>
<P>
Chile's early entry into NAFTA could spark renewed efforts throughout the rest of Latin America to push forward with difficult economic and political reforms. Chile's quick accession to NAFTA would be a powerful signal that, despite the Mexican crisis, the U.S. remains strongly committed to supporting free trade and structural economic reform in the Western Hemisphere and that there is a real reward ahead for countries that persevere in the creation of free-market democracies.
<p>
The time to act is now. This must be done before the region loses the sense of urgency that has driven the reform process since the end of the 1980s. Latin America has made a quantum leap forward in terms of economic liberalization and democratic reform, but there is always the risk that the region could backslide to its statist, interventionist past. Venezuela already has done so, while in Mexico a growing chorus of critics are wrongly blaming the peso's collapse on the free-market policies of the Salinas and Zedillo governments. In both Mexico and the U.S., the enemies of NAFTA once again are urging its abolition.
<p>
The expansion of NAFTA to include Chile presents the U.S. with a major opportunity to receive full credit for developing the vision of a free trade area encompassing all of the Americas. U.S. influence would increase significantly throughout the region if Chile were included in NAFTA. Moreover, U.S. exporters, investors, and workers would be direct beneficiaries of this enhanced influence thanks to America's fast-growing trade with the rest of the region.
<P>
But NAFTA's expansion to include Chile, and subsequently other Latin American countries, will not be a free ride for the United States. Instead, it will demand a minimum level of accountability from U.S. trade policy. The rhythm and conditionality of Chile's accession to NAFTA will be followed closely by other potential candidates for membership, such as Argentina and others in the Andean and Caribbean regions. Depending on the outcome of Chile's negotiations to join NAFTA, these countries could be encouraged to reform their economies with the goal of attaining NAFTA-level standards. However, if they are spurned by the U.S., they may seek alternatives such as Mercosur or the recently created Association of Caribbean states, whose members include NAFTA partner Mexico and communist Cuba, among others, but not the United States.
<p>
If the U.S. expects to be viewed as a legitimate champion of free trade in the world, and if it wants to be viewed in Latin America as the region's natural leader, the Clinton Administration and Congress must reach agreement quickly on a new fast track negotiating authority to implement Chile's accession to NAFTA. Moreover, the bill approved by Congress and accepted by the Clinton Administration should be a clean bill, without language on labor or environmental issues. In addition, the U.S. must implement a stable, predictable trade policy with regard to Latin America -- one that avoids the threat of unilateral actions against the region's economies and also resists pressures by special-interest groups to impose a non-trade agenda that would pose a threat to development. These are the challenges facing the U.S. as it negotiates Chile's membership in NAFTA.
<p>
<p> <center><a href="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0
></a></center>
<p></body></html>

  
